        "More than two hundred years ago, there was a German musician named Beethoven who composed many famous works. Among them was a renowned piano piece called the 'Moonlight Sonata.' Legend has it that it was composed like this.",
        "One autumn, Beethoven was traveling and performing. He came to a small town on the bank of the Rhine. One evening, as he strolled along a quiet path, he heard the halting notes of a piano drifting from a thatched cottage—someone was playing his music.",
        "Beethoven approached the cottage. The playing suddenly stopped, and voices came from inside. A girl said, 'This piece is so hard to play! I've only heard others play it a few times, and I can never remember how it goes. If only I could hear Beethoven himself play it—how wonderful that would be!' A man said, 'Yes, but concert tickets are too expensive, and we are too poor.' The girl said, 'Brother, don't be sad. I was just talking.'",
        "Hearing this, Beethoven pushed open the door and quietly walked in. A single candle lit the cottage. In the faint candlelight, the man was making shoes. By the window stood an old piano, and before it sat a girl of sixteen or seventeen with a delicate face—but her eyes were blind.",
        "The shoemaker saw a stranger enter and stood up to ask, 'Sir, who are you looking for? Have you come to the wrong door?' Beethoven said, 'No, I've come to play a piece for this young lady.'",
        "The girl quickly stood up to offer her seat. Beethoven sat at the piano and played the piece the blind girl had just been practicing. She listened, spellbound. When the piece ended, she said excitedly, 'Such mastery! Such deep feeling! You—you must be Beethoven himself!'",
        "Beethoven did not answer. He asked the blind girl, 'Did you enjoy it? Let me play another for you.'",
        "A gust of wind blew out the candle. Moonlight streamed through the window, draping everything in the cottage with silver gauze, making it extraordinarily serene. Beethoven looked at the brother and sister standing beside him, and in the gentle moonlight, he began to press the keys.",
        "The shoemaker listened quietly. It was as if he were facing the sea, with the moon rising where water met sky. In an instant, silver light scattered across the rippling surface. The moon rose higher and higher, passing through wisps of cloud like veils of gauze. Suddenly, a great wind swept over the sea, raising enormous waves. Crests of foam, lit brilliant white by the moon, surged one after another toward the shore...",
        "The shoemaker glanced at his sister. Moonlight fell on her tranquil face and her wide-open eyes. It was as though she too could see—could see what she had never seen before: a vast, surging sea under the moonlight.",
        "The brother and sister were intoxicated by the beautiful music. By the time they came to their senses, Beethoven had long since left the cottage. He rushed back to his inn and spent the entire night recording the piece he had just played—the 'Moonlight Sonata.'"
